  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The underlying philosophy behind privacy attacks lies in the correlation between the level of accessibility an adversary holds and its ability to extract sensitive information or exert control over target victim LLMs.",
    "More access leads to a broader potential for the adversary to recover sensitive data or influence the target LLM [131].",
    "For instance, when the adversary has access only to the black-box model, the attacker might be able to leverage training data extraction attacks to recover a limited set of private data.",
    "However, if the adversary is granted white-box information such as gradients, the attacker can leverage this extra information to accurately recover more private training instances [55].",
    "This expanded access can facilitate various privacy attacks, including attribute inference attacks, embedding inversion, and gradient leakage attacks."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
